(46, 14, 'description', 'The myKrobe predictor is designed for use by doctors. It analyses the whole genome of a bacterial sample and provides the information a doctor needs in order to choose a treatment, all within a couple of minutes. No expertise is needed to run or interpret it, and it works on a standard desktop or laptop.'),
(47, 14, '_description', 'field_534e14b5161c9'),
(48, 14, 'screenshot', ''),
(49, 14, '_screenshot', 'field_534e14cf08e27'),
(50, 14, 'species_0_title', 'S.Aureus'),
(51, 14, '_species_0_title', 'field_534e152766e4b'),
(52, 14, 'species_0_description', 'Our first (beta) release is the predictor for Staphylococcus. Given a blood culture sample which is positive for Gram stain, the myKrobe predictor will determine which species the sample is, and if Staphylococcus aureus, it will predict the resistance profile for 12 key antibiotics, including quinoloines, macrolides/lincosamides, beta-lactams and tetracyclines.'),
(53, 14, '_species_0_description', 'field_534e153a66e4c'),
(54, 14, 'species_0_small_print', 'Technical specs: Runs on Windows and Linux, requires ~500Mb of RAM, takes between 40 seconds and 3 minutes to run Sequencing: Supports Illumina and Oxford Nanopore Technology sequencing data. Antibiotics supported: Beta-lactams (methicillin, penicillin), quinolones (ciprofloxacin), macrolides/lincosamides (erythromycin, clindamycin), tetracycline, aminoglycosides (gentamicin), glycopeptides (vancomycin), rifampicin, mupirocin, fusidic acid, trimethoprim. Predictive performance: Although not yet certified for clinical use, our tests on 992 samples show false negative rate of 0.3% (predicting susceptible when actually resistant) and false positive rate of 0.5% (predicting resistant when susceptible) which are below the requirements for FDA approval. See our paper for details.'),
(55, 14, '_species_0_small_print', 'field_534e154566e4d'),
(56, 14, 'species', '1'),
(57, 14, '_species', 'field_534e14fc5dcdc'),
(58, 10, 'description', 'The Mykrobe predictor is designed for use by microbiologists and doctors, providing information needed in order to choose the best treatment. It analyses the whole genome of a bacterial sample, all within a couple of minutes, and predicts which drugs the infection is resistant to. No expertise is needed to run or interpret it, and it works on a standard desktop or laptop.'),
(59, 10, '_description', 'field_534e14b5161c9'),
(60, 10, 'screenshot', '48'),
(61, 10, '_screenshot', 'field_534e14cf08e27'),
(62, 10, 'species_0_title', 'MRSA'),
(63, 10, '_species_0_title', 'field_534e152766e4b'),
(64, 10, 'species_0_description', '<em>Staphylococcus aureus</em> is a major cause of infections across the world. When resistant to the antibiotic methicillin, it is known as the \"superbug\" MRSA.\r\n\r\nFor <em>S. aureus, s</em>tandard procedure in a hospital is that a patient sample undergoes \"blood culture\" overnight, and a very rapid \"Gram stain\" test to establish that the infection is one of the family of species called staphylococci. If the DNA in this sample is then sequenced, the Mykrobe predictor takes that raw output data, which typically requires hours of analysis and interpretation, and within minutes identifies the species, checks for contamination, and predicts the resistance profile for 12 key antibiotics, including quinolones, macrolides/lincosamides, beta-lactams and tetracyclines. It will also test for the presence of Panton-Valentin Leukocidin toxin.'),
(65, 10, '_species_0_description', 'field_534e153a66e4c'),
(66, 10, 'species_0_small_print', 'Runs on Windows, Mac OS X and Linux, requires ~300Mb of RAM, takes between 40 seconds and 3 minutes to run.\r\n\r\nSequencing: Supports Illumina sequencing data as standard. Antibiotics supported: Beta-lactams (methicillin, penicillin), quinolones (ciprofloxacin), macrolides/lincosamides (erythromycin, clindamycin), tetracycline, aminoglycosides (gentamicin), glycopeptides (vancomycin), rifampicin, mupirocin, fusidic acid, trimethoprim.\r\n\r\nSupport for Oxford Nanopore Technology sequencing data is in development.\r\n\r\nPredictive performance: Although not yet certified for clinical use, our tests on 992 samples show false negative rate of 0.3% (predicting susceptible when actually resistant) and false positive rate of 0.5% (predicting resistant when susceptible). See our paper for details.\r\n\r\nCitation:\r\n\r\nBradley, Phelim, et al. \"Rapid antibiotic-resistance predictions from genome sequence data for Staphylococcus aureus and Mycobacterium tuberculosis.\"<i>Nature communications</i> 6 (2015).'),
(67, 10, '_species_0_small_print', 'field_534e154566e4d'),
