(1243, 91, '_species_1_teaser_description', 'field_5354a337f7d9b'),
(1244, 91, 'species_1_description', '<em>Mycobacterium tuberculosis</em> infects perhaps one third of the world population and causes the disease TB. In 2013 there were an estimated 450,000 cases of multi-drug resistant cases of TB, and there is an urgent need for fast and accurate diagnostics. Standard drug susceptibility testing takes 6 weeks, during which a patient may be receiving ineffective treatment due to resistant bacteria. If instead samples undergo \"liquid culture\" followed by DNA sequencing and Mykrobe predictor analysis, <em>the time to results is reduced by about 1 month</em>. If drug resistance is detected, this will allow treatment to be modified immediately. This is not a complete solution - we do not fully understand the genetic basis of drug resistance on <em>M. tuberculosis</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFor <em>M. tuberculosis</em>, the Mykrobe predictor identifies if the sample is from the <em>M. tuberculosis</em> complex (and if so, which species) or is an \"atypical mycobacterium\", and then predicts drug resistance for 3 first-line drugs (rifampicin, isoniazid, ethambutol) and also second-line drugs (streptomycin, aminoglycosides, quinolones). Unusually for DNA-based diagnostics, the Mykrobe predictor detects rare \"minor\" populations of drig resistant bacteria, which may later spread, and our analyses suggest this gives the Mykrobe predictor greater ability to detect drug resistance for 2nd line drugs, a critical component of dealing with MDR-TB.'),
