(53, 2, '2014-04-25 12:43:25', '2014-04-25 12:43:25', '<h3>Mission</h3>\r\nRecent advances in genome sequencing and in web technologies have taken us to the the edge of a new world, where studying the genomes of microbial samples could lead to enormous benefits for public health, clinical treatments and the study of infectious diseases. However in order to make this a reality we need tools to enable clinicians, public health workers and biologists to make decisions and discoveries. Our goals with the myKrobe suite of tools are\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>To provide extremely user-friendly tools which enable people to study specific microbial samples, either in and of themselves, or in the context of global diversity.</li>\r\n	<li>To enable seamless world-wide sharing of microbial genomes.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nMyKrobe was developed at the <a href=\"http://www.well.ox.ac.uk/\">Wellcome Trust Centre for Human Genetics</a> (University of Oxford) in Zamin Iqbal’s lab, by himself and Phelim Bradley, in collaboration with Claire Gordon, Tanya Golubchik, Louise Pankhurst, Luke Anson, Tim Peto and Derrick Crooke at the John Radcliffe Hospital, Oxford.', 'About', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '17-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-04-25 12:43:25', '2014-04-25 12:43:25', '', 17, 'http://www.mykrobe.com//2014/04/25/17-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
